\pard\plain\s6\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs24\sl360\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 The Rayleigh Limit\par
\~\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl360\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Lord Rayleigh appraised a limit of resolution in an optical system in terms of the separation of two Airy disc point spread functions. Rayleigh defined the limit as the distance when the maximum of the PSF is positioned on top of the first minima of the other. This definition implies a contrast between the two functions of {27}{}; if the intensity trough seen from two airy discs in a microscope is lower than that, then by Rayleigh\rquote s criterion (see Equation{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMeq_rayleigh \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{1.6}}}) the two objects cannot confidently be resolved, see Figure{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMfig_rayleighlimit \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{1.3}}}.\par
