}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl360\slmult1 \fi0 Non-optical far field techniques can resolve much smaller than the diffraction limit. However, each is limited in its biological imaging capacity. Electron microscopy uses electrons instead of photons to observe Angstrom sized particleRuska1941. An electron microscope is limited by its De Broglie wavelength, the effective size of an electron, on the pico meter scaleAhmed2011. Electron microscopes are impractical for {\i in vivo} biological studies, as high intensity electron beams require conductive dissipater coatings which impede and damage biological processes.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl360\slmult1 \fi360 Atomic force microscopes use sensitive piezo crystals to position and record surface information from samples using a cantilever at the nanometre scaleBinnig1988. The tip of an AFM is convolved with the profile of the surface and so is limited in resolution to the size of an atom. Atomic force microscopes are slow raster scanning imaging techniques but more crucially offer no sample specificity, which is requisite to biology as it involves querying how two biological agents interact or how an agent acts in environment: e.g observing diseased cell interactions in a mouse brain modelMisgeld2006, monitoring cancerous tumoursHoffman2005 and understanding virus structurePereira2012.\par
